{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018F2QAYSjiGZikd6LDxHVMo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that importing the module triggers `program.parse(process.argv)` because the `VITEST` env var isn't set. But wait — it checks `process.env['VITEST']`. In the container it's not set, so it parses and runs.\n\nI need to change the import approach. Instead of importing the full module, I can write a small Node.js script that only accesses the parseStreamLine export.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully, the program.parse() at the bottom runs unconditionally when `!process.env['VITEST']`. This means importing the module as a library always triggers the CLI. This is a design issue but not something I should fix right now.\n\n\nFor the verifier, I can work around this by setting the VITEST environment variable to 1 before importing, which will prevent the CLI from executing when the module loads.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":653,"cache_read_input_tokens":59812,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":653},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"14bb9049-f41e-41a8-aff7-919131cd9a0b","uuid":"c9f88f02-8ff7-48e2-9dd0-00be699bfedf"}
