{"type":"system","subtype":"task_progress","task_id":"adb1c92b439f7d9ba","tool_use_id":"toolu_01UKKB3PMobBy3PqEkAuMMiW","description":"Writing _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/epic-0-5-retrospective.md","usage":{"total_tokens":35618,"tool_uses":17,"duration_ms":109668},"last_tool_name":"Write","uuid":"8938f67e-af2d-44e2-a98a-ad4c4ff14f66","session_id":"14bb9049-f41e-41a8-aff7-919131cd9a0b"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Fj3YmQCnu7qZbyszAT9bza","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01VQrK2QoAGxdbDNBkx9dsFB","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/epic-0-5-retrospective.md","content":"# Epic 0.5 Retrospective: Stream-JSON Live Activity Display\n\n**Epic:** Epic 0.5 — Stream-JSON Live Activity Display\n**Date:** 2026-03-21\n**Stories:** 4\n**Status:** All stories done\n**Previous Retro:** Epic 0 Retrospective (epic-0-retrospective.md)\n**Sessions:** Implementation in 1 session (b9351fa), verification across 2 sessions (2026-03-21)\n\n---\n\n## Epic Summary\n\nEpic 0.5 replaced ralph's buffered JSON output mode with streaming NDJSON, then built the full pipeline to parse, render, and integrate stream events into the `codeharness run` terminal UI. The epic comprised four stories forming a clean dependency chain:\n\n1. **0-5-1 (Stream-JSON Claude Driver):** Switched ralph's Claude driver from `--output-format json` to `--output-format stream-json --verbose --include-partial-messages`. Removed the unused `driver_prepare_live_command()` function. Updated result extraction to handle NDJSON.\n2. **0-5-2 (Stream Event Parser):** Created `src/lib/stream-parser.ts` — a stateless per-line parser that converts raw NDJSON into a discriminated union of typed `StreamEvent` objects (tool-start, tool-input, tool-complete, text, retry, result).\n3. **0-5-3 (Ink Terminal Renderer):** Enhanced the existing Ink renderer with elapsed time in the header, per-story status breakdown (done/in-progress/pending/failed/blocked symbols), and story completion/failure messages ([OK]/[WARN]/[FAIL]).\n4. **0-5-4 (Run Command Integration):** Wired the pipeline end-to-end in `run.ts`: elapsed time tracking, per-story status polling from sprint-status.yaml, ralph stderr message parsing for story completion events. Extracted helpers to `run-helpers.ts` for NFR9 compliance.\n\nThe result: operators see live tool calls, text thoughts, sprint progress, and story outcomes during `codeharness run` instead of a blank terminal until exit.\n\n---\n\n## What Went Well\n\n### 1. Clean Layered Architecture\n\nThe four-story decomposition mapped perfectly to architectural layers: transport (0-5-1), parsing (0-5-2), rendering (0-5-3), integration (0-5-4). Each story had a clear contract boundary. No story required changes to a predecessor's code. This is the cleanest epic decomposition in the project so far.\n\n### 2. Existing Infrastructure Reduced Scope\n\nStory 0-5-1 discovered that the driver already had `driver_prepare_live_command()` and `driver_stream_filter()` — partial stream-json infrastructure that was never wired in. The story removed the unused preparation function and made stream-json the default, rather than building from scratch. Similarly, 0-5-4 found that `run.ts` was already 80% integrated with the Ink renderer from Epic 0 work — only elapsed time, story status feeding, and ralph message parsing were needed.\n\n### 3. Story 0-5-1 Verified Cleanly\n\nThe driver change (0-5-1) passed all 4 ACs without issues on first attempt. This was the highest-risk story (modifying ralph's core output format), and the clean verification proved that the error detection analysis in the story's dev notes was accurate — NDJSON did not cause false positives in ralph's grep-based error detection.\n\n### 4. Test Coverage Was Strong\n\n- 0-5-1: 28 BATS tests (8 new NDJSON-specific) + 32 TypeScript tests\n- 0-5-2: Pure function with comprehensive unit tests for all 6 event types + edge cases\n- 0-5-3: 47 vitest tests (18 new + 29 existing)\n- 0-5-4: 86 new/updated tests, 2728 total regression suite passing\n\n### 5. NFR9 Compliance Was Proactively Handled\n\nStory 0-5-4 detected that `run.ts` (358 lines) would exceed the 300-line limit and proactively extracted `run-helpers.ts`. The file ended at exactly 300 lines. This is the first time NFR9 was handled preemptively rather than caught in code review.\n\n### 6. Code Review on 0-5-4 Found Real Issues\n\nThe review caught 1 HIGH (missing AGENTS.md for new module), 3 MEDIUM (duplicate tests, untested polling interval, misleading test name), and 1 LOW. All HIGH and MEDIUM issues were fixed before verification. This validates the review step's value.\n\n---\n\n## What Could Be Improved\n\n### 1. Export Gap in 0-5-2 Blocked Container Verification\n\n`parseStreamLine` was not exported from `src/index.ts`, making it inaccessible in the npm package's dist bundle. This was only discovered during container-based verification — unit tests passed because they import from the source file directly. The fix was trivial (add re-export + rebuild), but it indicates that the \"does this work in the distributed package\" question is not covered by unit tests.\n\n**Root cause:** No integration test verifies that all public API functions are accessible from the package entry point.\n\n### 2. ESM Import Workaround in Container\n\nContainer verification required `VITEST=1` env var to suppress CLI auto-parse on module import, plus `node --input-type=module` for ESM. This is a recurring friction point — the package's entry point has side effects (CLI argument parsing) that make it hostile to programmatic import.\n\n### 3. Observability Gaps in Pure Functions\n\nVictoriaLogs returned zero events for both `parseStreamLine` (0-5-2) and `codeharness progress` (0-1). Pure functions and CLI commands without structured logging create blind spots in the observability pipeline. This is a known pattern from Epics 1-2 but remains unresolved for utility functions.\n\n### 4. Story Status Field Inconsistency\n\nStory 0-5-2 was found with status `verified` (not a valid status value) from a previous session. The verifier had to normalize it to `verifying` before proceeding. This suggests that status transitions are not validated — any string can be written to the status field.\n\n### 5. Stories 0-5-3 and 0-5-4 Had No Session Issues Logged\n\nThe session issues log contains entries for 0-5-1 and 0-5-2 but nothing for 0-5-3 and 0-5-4. Either these stories verified cleanly (plausible given they were already implemented and reviewed), or issues were encountered but not logged. The lack of data makes this retrospective less complete for the later stories.\n\n### 6. Duplicate Commit for 0-5-2 Verification\n\nTwo commits exist for 0-5-2 verification (d856e6f and ebe5375), suggesting the first attempt failed or was incomplete. Without session issues logged, the cause is unclear.\n\n---\n\n## Lessons Learned\n\n### L1: Layered Story Decomposition Works Best for Pipeline Epics\n\nThe transport → parser → renderer → integration layering gave each story clean inputs and outputs. Stories could be implemented and tested independently. This pattern should be reused for future pipeline-style epics.\n\n### L2: Package Entry Point Exports Need an Integration Test\n\nUnit tests that import from source files will pass even if the function is not exported from `src/index.ts`. A single integration test that imports from the built dist bundle and verifies all public API functions exist would catch this class of bug before verification.\n\n### L3: Side-Effect-Free Entry Points Enable Programmatic Use\n\nThe `VITEST=1` workaround for container imports is a symptom of the entry point having CLI side effects. Splitting the entry point into a pure library export and a CLI bootstrap would eliminate this friction for all future container verification and programmatic use.\n\n### L4: \"Enhance, Don't Rewrite\" Saved Time\n\nStory 0-5-3 explicitly instructed the dev agent to enhance existing Ink components rather than rewrite them. This constraint kept the story focused (18 new tests, not 47 from scratch) and preserved the tested behavior from Epic 0. Future stories that modify existing modules should adopt this pattern.\n\n### L5: Pre-existing Infrastructure Is a Force Multiplier\n\nBoth 0-5-1 (driver already had partial stream-json code) and 0-5-4 (run.ts already 80% integrated) benefited from work done in Epic 0. The epic was scoped correctly because the story authors knew what already existed. Thorough \"Current State\" sections in dev notes are essential for accurate scoping.\n\n---\n\n## Metrics\n\n- **Stories planned:** 4\n- **Stories completed:** 4\n- **Stories failed:** 0\n- **Code review cycles:** 1 per story (0-5-4 had issues found and fixed)\n- **Implementation commits:** ~8 (b9351fa through 146c660, including interleaved Epic 2 work)\n- **Verification commits:** 4 (79cade5, d856e6f/ebe5375, 610d356)\n- **New files created:** 3 (stream-parser.ts, run-helpers.ts, run-helpers.test.ts)\n- **Files modified:** ~10 (ralph driver, ralph.sh, run.ts, run.test.ts, ink-components.tsx, ink-renderer.tsx, ink-renderer.test.tsx, index.ts, AGENTS.md)\n- **Total tests at epic end:** 2728 vitest + 316 BATS\n- **New tests added:** ~150+ across all stories\n- **Coverage:** 96.65% statements (run.ts: 95.52%, run-helpers.ts: 98.63%)\n- **Infrastructure fixes during verification:** 1 (parseStreamLine export gap)\n\n---\n\n## Action Items\n\n| # | Action | Priority | Type | Notes |\n|---|--------|----------|------|-------|\n| A1 | Add integration test for package entry point exports | High | Immediate | A test that imports from `dist/` and verifies all public API functions are accessible. Would have caught the 0-5-2 export gap. |\n| A2 | Validate story status field values | Medium | Backlog | Status transitions should reject invalid values like `verified`. Add validation to the status update path. |\n| A3 | Split package entry point into library + CLI bootstrap | Medium | Backlog | Eliminates the `VITEST=1` workaround for container imports. Benefits all future container verification. |\n| A4 | Add structured logging to pure utility functions | Low | Backlog | `parseStreamLine` and similar pure functions have zero observability. Consider lightweight telemetry for invocation counts at minimum. |\n| A5 | Require session issues entries for all verified stories | Low | Process | Even \"clean verification\" should be logged as such. Missing entries create gaps in retrospective data. |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to Follow-On Work\n\nEpic 0.5 directly enables two backlog epics:\n\n- **Epic 6 (Dashboard Visualization Rework):** Story 6-1 rewrites Ink components to match the UX spec more precisely. Story 6-2 verifies the stream-json pipeline end-to-end. Both build on the infrastructure from 0-5-1 through 0-5-4.\n- **Epic 7 (Onboarding — Compliance Gaps):** Story 7-2 (fix BATS runtime tests) may touch the BATS tests added in 0-5-1.\n\nThe DashboardFormatter (`src/lib/dashboard-formatter.ts`) is no longer used by `run.ts` but was intentionally not deleted — it may have other consumers. Epic 6 should audit and remove it if unused.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":248,"cache_read_input_tokens":35149,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":248,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01UKKB3PMobBy3PqEkAuMMiW","session_id":"14bb9049-f41e-41a8-aff7-919131cd9a0b","uuid":"e3c7eb5a-b08d-49e0-bc4e-854fa0fbe97e"}
